ame time, it is a theoretically ambitious attempt to think through our very relationship with technology and our possible ecological futures. Fisch provides an unblinking glimpse into what it might be like to inhabit a future in which more and more of our infrastructure—and the planet itself—will have to operate beyond capacity to accommodate our ever-growing population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aRailroadszJapanzTokyoxCommuting traffic. 0aUrban transportationxSocial aspectszJapanzTokyo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCollective.  aCommuter train network.  aFukushima.  aGilbert Simondon.  aInfrastructure.  aJapan.  aMachine.  aMedia.  aScience and Technology Studies.  aTechnology.  aTokyo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z978311063851640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226558691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226558691/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles